        "urlbase": "/th?id=OHR.MaldivesWhaleShark_ROW7272953722",
        "copyright": "Whale shark off the coast of Alifu Dhaalu Atoll, Maldives (© Bachir Moukarzel/Amazing Aerial Agency)",
        "copyrightlink": "https://www.bing.com/search?q=Whale+shark&form=hpcapt",
        "title": "Info",
        "quiz": "/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:%22HPQuiz_20250830_MaldivesWhaleShark%22&FORM=HPQUIZ",
        "wp": true,
        "md5": "59a5d916db629f0f7e833e5c24ca57f3",
        "hsh": "ad36cb2561d47c866cc3f8b17888e014",
        "drk": 1,
        "top": 1,
        "bot": 1,
        "hs": [],
        "MediaContent": {
            "ImageContent": {
                "Description": "Whale sharks are the biggest fish in the sea, but don't let the word 'shark' fool you. They're plankton-eating giants with no interest in humans. Found in warm waters from the Maldives and Mozambique to Mexico's Yucatán coast, they often show up in food-rich, calm waters. Their mouths can stretch over a metre wide, but they feed by suction, not biting. Each has a unique pattern of white spots and stripes—no two alike—used by researchers to track individuals. Their breeding patterns remain largely a mystery, but they are ovoviviparous, meaning pups hatch inside the mother before being born alive. Their story reminds us how much ocean life remains a mystery and how vital it is to protect what we already know is at risk.",
                "Image": {
                    "Url": "/th?id=OHR.MaldivesWhaleShark_ROW7272953722_1920x1080.webp",
                    "Wallpaper": "/th?id=OHR.MaldivesWhaleShark_ROW7272953722_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg",
                    "Downloadable": true
                },
                "Headline": "Info",
                "Title": "Whale shark off the coast of Alifu Dhaalu Atoll, Maldives",
                "Copyright": "© Bachir Moukarzel/Amazing Aerial Agency",
                "SocialGood": null,
                "MapLink": {
